vision, this collection also examines how the celebrity of the late MTV star Pedro Zamora countered racist and homophobic discourses; reveals how news coverage on drug use shifted from the white middle-class cocaine user in the early 1980s to the black "crack mother" of the 1990s; and takes on TV coverage of the Rodney King beating and the subsequent unrest in Los Angeles. Other essays consider O.J. Simpson's murder trial, comparing television's treatment of Simpson to that of Michael Jackson, Magic Johnson, Michael Jordan, and Clarence Thomas and look at the racism directed at Asian Americans by the recurring "Dancing Itos" on Jay Leno's Tonight Show.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh1 aLocke, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaficy, Hamid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReeves, Jimmie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunoz, Jose Esteban, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite, Mimi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Phillip Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorres, Sasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBest, Stephen Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorres, Sasha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360